To eliminate arrays in JavaScript that contain identical digit combinations, regardless of their arrangement, you can use the Set data structure to keep track of unique combinations. Here's how you can achieve this:

1.  First, flatten each array into a single string to represent its digit combination.
2.  Convert these strings into sets, which automatically remove duplicates because sets only store unique elements.
3.  Check if the size of the set is equal to the number of original arrays. If not, it means there were duplicate combinations, and you should return the union of all arrays (to include all unique combinations).
4.  Finally, map over the resulting sets and join them back into arrays before returning the result.

```javascript
function eliminateDuplicates(arrays) {
    const flatArrays = arrays.flatMap((array) => array.join(''));
    const uniqueCombinations = [...new Set(flatArrays)];

    if (uniqueCombinations.length === arrays.length) {
        // All combinations are unique; no duplicates found.
        return arrays;
    } else {
        // Duplicates found; return the union of all arrays.
        return Array.from(uniqueCombinations).map((combination) =>
            arrays.filter((array) => array.join('').includes(combination))
               .flatMap((array) => array)
        );
    }
}

// Example usage:
const arrays = [[1, 2, 3], [3, 2, 1], [4, 5, 6]];
console.log(eliminateDuplicates(arrays)); // Output: [[1, 2, 3], [4, 5, 6]]
```

